  <sec id="SEC5">
    <title>5 EXTRACTING MEMBERS OF BICLUSTERS</title>
    <p>After model selection and ranking of bicluster, the <italic>i</italic>-th bicluster has <italic>soft gene memberships</italic> given by the absolute values of <bold>Œª</bold><sub><italic>i</italic></sub> and <italic>soft sample memberships</italic> given by the absolute values of <bold><italic>z</italic></bold><sub><italic>i</italic></sub><sup><italic>T</italic></sup>. Soft clustering has the advantage that gradual memberships are able to account for ambiguities that occur in gene expression datasets (where hard memberships can be obscured by noise). However, some applications require <italic>hard</italic> ‚Äò<italic>yes</italic>/<italic>no</italic>‚Äô <italic>memberships</italic>. We determine the members of the <italic>i</italic>-th bicluster by selecting absolute values Œª<sub><italic>ki</italic></sub> and <italic>z</italic><sub><italic>ij</italic></sub> above thresholds thresL and thresZ, respectively.</p>
